"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/oppenheimer-review-christopher-nolan-cillian-murphy-robert-downey-jr-atomic-bomb-be4ffc00"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831718?width=700&amp;height=489" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">环球影业</span></div></div></div><h4><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/oppenheimer-review-christopher-nolan-cillian-murphy-robert-downey-jr-atomic-bomb-be4ffc00?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">奥本海默 (2023)</a></h4><p> “这不是新武器。这是一个新世界。”在《奥本海默》中，当罗伯特·奥本海默 (J. Robert Oppenheimer) 研制原子弹时，有人这样评价道。 《奥本海默》对一位被称为“有史以来最重要的人”的物理学家的兴衰进行了一次充满智慧和令人窒息的探索。 ”就像这里将奥本海默与他进行比较的神话人物普罗米修斯一样，奥本海默也因其作品而受苦，从内到外都受到困扰。因此，一个本质上是关于一位毕生写方程的科学家的故事，在编剧兼导演克里斯托弗·诺兰的专业手中，变成了一锅沸腾的戏剧。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/oppenheimer-review-christopher-nolan-cillian-murphy-robert-downey-jr-atomic-bomb-be4ffc00?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读评论</a></p></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 21:36:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-best-biopics-of-the-21st- century-oppenheimer-ef971e66</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-best-biopics-of-the-21st- century-oppenheimer-ef971e66<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>音乐</category><category>运动的</category><category>冬季运动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>音乐</category><category>运动的</category><category>冬季运动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Legal Assault on Corporate Diversity Efforts Has Begun]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>保守派团体使用许多与扼杀大学平权行动计划相同的工具来挑战亚马逊、康卡斯特和其他公司<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831356/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>埃米尔·伦多夫/华尔街日报<span>埃米尔·伦多夫/华尔街日报</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116214"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116214"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/theo-francis" itemprop="url" rel="author">西奥·弗朗西斯</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lauren-weber" itemprop="url" rel="author">劳伦·韦伯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-equity-dei-companies-blum-2040b173"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>保守派法律活动人士<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-rules-against-affirmative-action-c94b5a9c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">成功挑战了</a>大学使用平权行动。现在，他们正在寻求在美国企业中广泛部署的多元化举措。一些公司已经在重新考虑他们的努力。</p><p>在诉讼、股东信函和向平等就业机会委员会提交的请愿书中，活动人士使用了一些与进步团体用来推进多样性、公平和包容性（DEI）计划相同的策略。他们认为，公司违反了反对种族和性别歧视的规则，包括旨在保护美国黑人权利的立法中制定的规则。</p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CMCSA" class="company-name">康卡斯特</a>解决了一起指控其通过赠款和营销建议非法偏袒少数族裔小型企业客户的案件。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="company-name">亚马逊</a>因一项向黑人或拉丁裔拥有的送货服务承包商额外提供 10,000 美元的计划而在德克萨斯州被起诉。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SBUX" class="company-name">星巴克</a>董事和高管被股东起诉，称他们支持多元化政策，违反了对投资者的义务。</p><p>数十家公司律师事务所和主要雇主收到了共和党官员的来信，警告他们遵守禁止就业和合同决策中种族配额和偏好的法律。</p><p>爱德华·布鲁姆（Edward Blum）也<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/affirmative-action-supreme-court-ed-blum-100b36c3" target="_blank" class="icon none">组织了这场挑战</a>，最终导致美国最高法院<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-rules-against-affirmative-action-c94b5a9c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">推翻平权行动</a>的决定，他利用最近成立的非营利组织起诉佐治亚州投资管理公司无畏基金（Fearless Fund），指控针对初创企业的资助计划具有歧视性。 Fearless 对有色人种女性经营的企业进行早期投资。</p><p>公司表示，他们的举措符合法律规定。许多人表示，他们仍然致力于增加劳动力和供应商的人口多样性，理由是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-business-case-for-more-diversity-11572091200" target="_blank" class="icon none">商业利益</a>和一些群体在美国公司中继续面临的障碍。</p><p>私下里， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/companiesexpectnew-challenges-todiversitypolicies-after-court-ruling-4bf48c1d" target="_blank" class="icon none">许多人询问他们的律师，</a>根据平权行动的决定，他们是否应该以及多少程度地修改他们的方法。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828205?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">针对亚马逊的一项联邦诉讼针对的是一项向黑人、拉丁裔和美洲原住民送货服务承包商额外奖励 10,000 美元的计划，以支付启动成本。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Kathy Tran/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>许多针对企业多元化计划的法律努力早于高等法院 6 月 29 日的裁决。这项裁决主要针对高等教育招生，并未涉及就业或商业行为。</p><p>但这为保守派活动人士和公职人员挑战企业多元化计划的努力增添了动力。长期以来，企业一直依赖类似于大学里支持平权行动的理由——多元化有好处。通过驳回这一理由，高等法院削弱了其他推广该理由的项目的理由。</p><p>威斯康星州前副检察长兼副法律顾问丹·列宁顿 (Dan Lennington) 表示：“公司所做的任何因种族而区别对待某人的行为，即使只是决策过程的一小部分，都将受到审查。”法律与自由研究所，康卡斯特诉讼背后的法律团体。</p><p>就业律师表示，其中一起案件提交最高法院可能只是时间问题。一些公司已经决定不会等待法院介入。全球 DEI 实践负责人安吉拉·伯格 (Angela Berg) 表示，对于 2020 年 5 月乔治·弗洛伊德在警方拘留期间被杀后迅速采取的计划来说尤其如此。在人力资源咨询公司美世 (Mercer) 工作，现在担任独立咨询顾问。</p><p>伯格表示，一些高管“从一开始就对股权计划感到不安”，他指的是指导或培训计划等举措。她说，最高法院改变了风险计算。</p><p>福特汉姆大学法学教授阿蒂努克·阿迪兰 (Atinuke Adediran) 表示，公司正在根据诉讼威胁评估多元化计划，这些威胁往往似乎是为了煽动公众恐惧。她收到了大公司人力资源官员协会关于这个问题的询问。 “公司为多元化所做的大部分事情都是合法的，”她说。 “公司可能需要做好保卫自己的准备。”</p><h3><strong>内战武器</strong></h3><p>有线电视巨头康卡斯特 (Comcast) 将一项小企业补助计划限制为至少 51% 股权由黑人、土著、有色人种或女性持有和经营的公司，该公司表示，这些人受到冠状病毒大流行的影响尤为严重。</p><p>威斯康星州法律与自由研究所在 2022 年 4 月起诉康卡斯特时援引了 1866 年《民权法案》。一项经常被称为第 1981 条的条款规定，所有美国人都应享有“与白人公民所享有的相同权利”，以起诉和执行合同。 The Wisconsin Institute, which says it supports litigation promoting “individual initiative and ordered liberty that leads to prosperity,” essentially turned that section on its head by gathering several white, male business owners as plaintiffs. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="503" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831273?width=700&amp;height=503" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Some activists cite a Civil War-era law that says all Americans should have the same rights to sue and enforce contracts &#39;as is enjoyed by white citizens.&#39; Pictured is a sketch by F. Dielman showing a celebration of the abolition of slavery in the District of Columbia, April 1866.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Library of Congress</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In mid-September, when Comcast announced the next round of grants, it <a href="https://corporate.comcast.com/press/releases/comcast-rise-investment-fund-grants-small-businesses-covid-19-pandemic)" target="_blank" class="icon none">opened the program</a> to all small businesses. Two months later, Comcast settled the litigation.</p><p> A Comcast spokesman declined to comment. In a news release about the program in May, Comcast described the program as evolving “from helping businesses survive the pandemic, to helping businesses and their communities thrive with a focus on economic growth.”</p><p> A federal lawsuit against Amazon.com filed outside Dallas in July 2022 also invokes the 1866 law.它的目标是向黑人、拉丁裔和美洲原住民送货服务承包商额外奖励 10,000 美元，以支付启动成本。该诉讼还批评了亚马逊旨在帮助黑人企业在亚马逊网站上销售产品的计划。</p><p> The plaintiff, a Denton County, Texas, resident, wants to apply to start an Amazon delivery-service contractor, but says she won&#39;t until the company eliminates the assistance for minority contractors or offers whites and Asians the same benefit, the complaint says. The plaintiff can&#39;t apply to become an Amazon delivery service partner “without subjecting herself to racial discrimination,” the lawsuit says.</p><p> The case seeks class-action status.该诉讼由包括美国第一法律公司总法律顾问在内的律师提交，该法律公司是华盛顿特区的一家非盈利组织，由前特朗普政府顾问斯蒂芬·米勒领导。 America First Legal describes itself as combating “an unholy alliance of corrupt special interests, big tech titans, the fake news media, and liberal Washington politicians.”</p><p> Amazon has moved to dismiss the lawsuit, saying its selection process for delivery contractors is race-neutral and that the plaintiff doesn&#39;t have standing to sue because she hasn&#39;t applied to be an Amazon contractor.</p><p> In court filings, the company calls her complaint “the epitome of an abstract and generalized grievance by a member of the general population about an internal corporate program that has no actual effect on her.”</p><p> Amazon declined to comment on the lawsuit. “我们相信多样性、公平和包容性的重要性，”一位发言人在一份书面声明中表示。 “We&#39;ll investigate the potential impact of any legal decisions on our programs and adjust as necessary to comply with the law.”</p><h3> <strong>The workplace discrimination argument</strong></h3><p> Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 bans workplace discrimination.最近的平权行动决定并未直接涉及就业实践。但最高法院法官尼尔·戈萨奇在一致意见中指出，高等教育和就业法律中关于歧视的“实质上相同的语言”。</p><p> Starbucks officers and directors were sued in August 2022 by National Center for Public Policy Research, a conservative think tank that owns 56 shares in the coffee chain.它指控星巴克违反了《第七章》和第 1981 条，并指责星巴克官员在就业、供应商合同和高管薪酬等领域采取违反反歧视法的政策，从而违反了对股东的信托义务。</p><p> Under the policies, Starbucks says it wants at least 30% of its workforce at all levels to be Black, indigenous or people of color by 2025. It plans to implement an analytics tool that lets managers see their progress and uses workforce diversity measures to help set executive pay.</p><p> Starbucks and company officials are seeking to dismiss the case, with a hearing scheduled for Friday.他们表示，NCPPR 并未表现出这些政策造成任何真正的损害，这些政策受到一项法律原则的保护，该原则赋予公司官员在经营业务时拥有广泛的自由裁量权，而且法院也支持多元化政策。他们说，放弃它们将使星巴克容易受到其他诉讼的影响。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="884" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828201?width=1260&amp;height=884" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Starbucks officers and directors were sued last year over policies that involve increasing workforce diversity at all levels of the coffee chain.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Mario Tama/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “We remain committed to creating a culture of warmth and belonging, where everyone is welcome,” a company spokeswoman said.</p><p> In court, Starbucks and its officials also argue NCPPR doesn&#39;t represent shareholders, who have rejected previous proxy proposals from the group suggesting Starbucks favors liberal or “woke” perspectives.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/KO" class="company-name">Coca-Cola</a> is among the companies that has already backtracked. 2021 年初，时任总法律顾问布拉德利·盖顿 (Bradley Gayton) 在致外部律师事务所的一封信中表示，这家汽水巨头 30% 的新法律工作应由女性、LGBTQ+、残疾人或少数种族和族裔群体成员的律师承担。信中称，律师事务所必须向可口可乐公司报告人口统计数据，如果不符合指导方针，可口可乐公司可能会降低费用。 Gayton stepped down from the role three months later.</p><p> American Civil Rights Project, a nonprofit law firm that also represents NCPPR in its Starbucks lawsuit, threatened to sue Coke on behalf of shareholders. In a letter to the company that June, the group called the policies “textbook violations” of Section 1981.</p><p> In early 2022 Gayton&#39;s successor, Monica Howard Doublas, wrote to the American Civil Rights Project that while the company remained fully committed to advancing DEI in the legal profession, she had contacted law firms to tell them the guidelines were never company policy.</p><h3> <strong>A chilling effect</strong></h3><p> America First Legal Foundation, the group backing the Texas lawsuit against Amazon, has written to the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, urging the four current commissioners to bypass the usual complaint process and open investigations into diversity practices at a range of brand-name companies.</p><p> Andrea Lucas, who was nominated to the commission by President Trump, declined to comment on the likelihood that she or other commissioners would open investigations.她表示，她认为许多企业多元化计划存在“重大法律和实际风险”。 “Equal opportunity is our charge,” she said of the agency&#39;s mission, “but the law does not demand equal outcomes.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830072?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Bradley Gayton, former general counsel at Coca-Cola, announced new guidelines for the makeup of attorneys doing legal work for the soda giant.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Coca-Cola/Business Wire</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Civil-rights lawyers say conservative activists&#39; arguments distort the original purpose of laws designed to protect groups that, historically, have had fewer labor-market opportunities or difficulty cracking corporate ceilings.</p><p> “The intent here is more political gain and a chilling effect—unfortunately it&#39;s effective,” said Katy Youker, an attorney with the Lawyers&#39; Committee for Civil Rights Under Law, which has been tracking challenges to corporate programs.</p><p> In Florida, a federal judge last year halted enforcement of provisions in HB 7, better known as the Stop Woke Act, which would have restricted private employers from conducting some diversity-related training.法官表示，这些措施侵犯了公司的言论自由权。 Gov. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/ron-desantis">Ron DeSantis</a> &#39;s administration has appealed the decision.</p><p> The pressure leaves employers vulnerable to litigation for either going too far or not far enough in addressing barriers to equity and inclusion, lawyers say.</p><p> “Employers still have obligations to comply with civil rights statutes,” said Charles McLaurin, senior counsel with the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund.他补充说，取消旨在扩大工作机会的 DEI 计划“有可能为某些边缘群体创造一个敌对的环境。 Companies would still face exposure.”</p><p> Write to Theo Francis at <a href="mailto:theo.francis@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">theo.francis@wsj.com</a> and Lauren Weber at <a href="mailto:Lauren.Weber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Lauren.Weber@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828197?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The administration of Florida Gov. Ron DeSantis appealed a federal judge&#39;s decision to halt enforcement of elements of what is known as the Stop Woke Act.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Daniel A. Varela/Miami Herald/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-equity-dei-companies-blum-2040b173</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-equity-dei-companies-blum-2040b173<author><![CDATA[Theo FrancisLauren Weber]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>wsjillustration</category><category>领导者</category><category>Broadcasting</category><category> Cable Broadcasting</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>Corporate Crime/Legal Action</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>Labor/Personnel</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Workplace Discrimination/Abuse</category><category> Affirmative Action</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>歧视</category><category>教育</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>社会问题</category><category>University/College</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> corporate crime</category><category>合法举动</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>labor</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>workplace discrimination</category><category>虐待</category><category>affirmative action</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>歧视</category><category>教育</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>社会问题</category><category>university</category><category> college</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>broadcasting</category><category> cable broadcasting</category><category>媒体</category><category>entertainment </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Elon Musk Calls Cybertruck Tesla’s ‘Best Product Ever.’ Here Comes the Test.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>卡车预计将于年底上市，比原计划晚两年<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116905"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B1A79903-5C46-4C69-8AC4-A0082045E182&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Felon-musk-calls-cybertruck-teslas-best-product-ever-here-comes-the-test-42095f45&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">特斯拉 Cyber​​truck 的推出是历史上最受期待的电动汽车发布之一。巴克莱分析师 Dan Levy 和 AlixPartners 的 Mark Wakefield 探讨了特斯拉首款皮卡将如何撼动皮卡市场。照片：弗雷德里克·布朗/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116905"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rebecca-elliott" itemprop="url" rel="author">丽贝卡·埃利奥特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-calls-cybertruck-teslas-best-product-ever-here-comes-the-test-42095f45"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk)</a>正在寻求用 Cyber​​truck 重新构想经典的美国皮卡，这是一款外观独特的卡车，采用全角度和未上漆的不锈钢材质。</p><p>现在，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="company-name">特斯拉</a>预计将在今年年底推出这款卡车，接下来的几个月将考验他是否能够执行这一愿景并交付该公司三年多来的第一辆新型乘用车。</p><p>事实证明，将 Cyber​​truck 推向市场已经充满挑战，多年来的延误包括设计变更、成本超支和流行病的不确定性。最新的转折发生在周一，这家电动汽车制造商宣布首席财务官扎克·柯克霍恩(Zach Kirkhorn) <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-finance-chief-zach-kirkhorn-steps-down-44e00ad?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">辞职</a>，他在保持公司成本稳定方面发挥了重要作用。</p><p>这款电动卡车的设计打破了传统皮卡的模式，具有三角形轮廓和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-unveiled-a-bullet-proof-pickup-then-the-window-broke-11574444427?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">防弹车身</a>。一些行业观察人士担心，这种设计独特的汽车对买家的吸引力有限，而且由于利润<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-tsla-q2-earnings-report-2023-9be2b571?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">已经受到压力，</a>开始生产的成本将损害盈利能力。</p><p>投资者押注这款卡车值得等待，并且它将为特斯拉品牌注入新的活力，该品牌的产品线比许多竞争对手都更老。</p><p>特斯拉投资者、未来基金管理合伙人加里·布莱克 (Gary Black) 表示：“Cyber​​truck 非常与众不同，它将让整个系列充满活力。”</p><p> Musk has been hyping the truck for years. He has called it the company&#39;s “best product ever” and has pitched the vehicle as a “badass, futuristic armored personnel carrier” that accelerates like a sports car and is packed with new technology. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831285?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Tesla has taken on manufacturing challenges with the Cybertruck, which uses stronger, heavier stainless steel instead of the sheet metal typically used in car bodies.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Robyn Beck/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In April, Musk said Tesla likely would begin <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-tsla-q1-earnings-report-2023-6b441d30?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">delivering the new pickups</a> in small numbers by the end of September. Output is expected to climb in 2024.</p><p> During the company&#39;s most recent call with Wall Street analysts, however, Musk sidestepped a question about pricing and delivery schedules. Instead, he said deliveries would come this year. He also echoed past warnings that beginning production of a new vehicle can be tricky.</p><p> “The production ramp will move as fast as the slowest and least lucky elements of the entire supply chain and internal production,” Musk said last month.</p><p> Tesla didn&#39;t respond to requests for comment.</p><p> Ramping up production of new vehicles has bedeviled Tesla, where Musk has described the launch of the Model 3 sedan several years ago as “production hell” that nearly killed the company.</p><p> Originally expected in 2021, the Cybertruck began to face challenges almost as soon as it was first shown in November 2019.</p><p> Within months, the Covid-19 pandemic was wreaking havoc on global supply chains and the Cybertruck took a back seat to surer bets designed to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-tsla-q4-earnings-report-2021-11643162910?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">quickly expand Tesla&#39;s market share</a> or <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-to-introduce-upgraded-model-s-to-jump-start-high-end-model-sales-11623334024?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">pad the bottom line</a> , people familiar with the matter said.</p><p> Later, as employees turned their attention to the Cybertruck, they struggled to deliver on their boss&#39;s promises while keeping a lid on costs. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="412" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831286?width=700&amp;height=412" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A Model Y on the factory floor at Tesla&#39;s &#39;Cyber Rodeo&#39; marking the opening last year of the company&#39;s factory outside of Austin, Texas.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jay Janner/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “You can make something infinitely desirable, but if it&#39;s not affordable, that will constrain people&#39;s ability to buy it because they don&#39;t have the money,” Musk said in January 2022, adding that he worried about making a truck that was within reach for Tesla&#39;s customers.</p><p> He initially promised <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-targets-u-s-auto-makers-profit-engine-with-electric-pickup-11574341200?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">three tiers of the truck</a> , starting with a $39,900 entry-level model and topping out at a higher-end version starting at $69,900. He has since said the pricing and specs would be different, citing inflation and “various issues” without sharing specifics.</p><p> The company has taken on an array of new manufacturing challenges with the Cybertruck, which uses stronger, heavier stainless steel instead of the sheet metal typically used in car bodies.</p><p> Tesla aimed to skip an expensive manufacturing step for the outer shell of the truck with stainless steel, which doesn&#39;t need to be painted because it is corrosion-resistant. However, it is rarely used to form vehicle bodies in part because it is less malleable than traditional materials. (DeLorean Motor&#39;s stainless-steel-bodied sports car was featured as the time machine in the “Back to the Future” films.)</p><p> “There&#39;s not industrywide knowledge of how to build stainless steel vehicles, and so there&#39;s a whole bunch of things nobody knows about that they&#39;re going to encounter,” said Doug Betts, president of JD Power&#39;s automotive division.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> And while Tesla excels in areas such as software and powertrain development, it has struggled with the process of building the car body, something the Cybertruck is likely to test, Betts said.</p><p> In addition to reimagining how pickup trucks should look, Musk wanted to upend how they are assembled. He envisioned a vehicle whose outer walls provide much of the overall structure.</p><p> “We moved the mass to the outside. We created an exoskeleton,” Musk said at the 2019 reveal.</p><p> However, Tesla has scaled back its exoskeleton ambitions, pursuing a more traditional vehicle design with an interior structure, people familiar with the matter said. The company did so, at least in part, to meet safety standards, one of the people said.</p><p> Some auto observers had expected more.</p><p> “It&#39;s unconventional in some areas, but for the most part it&#39;s a conventional build,” said Sandy Munro, an engineering consultant who tears apart cars and has reviewed pictures of early versions of the Cybertruck. “It&#39;s not the dramatic change that I was looking forward to,” he said, adding that he still thinks the vehicle will “take the market by storm.”</p><p> Musk has said he expects to make 250,000 or more Cybertrucks a year once output ramps up, making it a niche product in comparison to the company&#39;s best selling Model Y crossover. In total, Tesla sold about 1.3 million vehicles last year and is aiming to sell 20 million annually by 2030.</p><p> The Cybertruck&#39;s delays put it behind in a competitive segment where rivals have already brought their own EV pickups to market. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/F" class="">Ford Motor</a> <span class="company-name-type">&#39;s</span> F-150 Lightning, the top-selling electric pickup, starts at $49,995 after the company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-cuts-price-of-ev-f-150-lightning-truck-by-up-to-17-2cc21c6a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">slashed prices last month</a> . Rivian Automotive&#39;s competitor, the R1T, starts at $73,000.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Do you think Tesla&#39;s Cybertruck will ultimately be successful?为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Still, if Tesla can be successful, there is great potential. Full-size pickup trucks are the cash cow of the US auto industry, making up 13% of North American vehicle sales last year while being responsible for about 40% of profits, according to Wells Fargo.</p><p> Analysts expect early efforts to build Tesla&#39;s truck could further erode the company&#39;s profitability.</p><p> But the truck should eventually boost Tesla&#39;s profit margin if the company is able to deliver on its promises, said Anthony Wang, who co-leads the technology investing team at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TROW" class="">T. Rowe Price Associates</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> one of the company&#39;s largest shareholders.</p><p> “Whether the ramp comes this quarter or next, it doesn&#39;t really matter,” Wang said. “What matters more is: Can they execute on the cost and the specs?”</p><p>写信给丽贝卡·埃利奥特（Rebecca Elliott）： <a href="mailto:rebecca.elliott@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">rebecca.elliott@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/e1f7a12e-412d-41e7-b6c1-3f6c0615c7c1.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-calls-cybertruck-teslas-best-product-ever-here-comes-the-test-42095f45</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-calls-cybertruck-teslas-best-product-ever-here-comes-the-test-42095f45<author><![CDATA[Rebecca Elliott]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>Automotive</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>特斯拉</category><category>特斯拉</category><category>埃隆·马斯克</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>automotive </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Credit Card, PayPal or Cash App? How You Pay Matters]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> A guide to weighing security, convenience and benefits of each payment option <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001113428"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831133?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Various payment methods provide different conveniences, perks and protections from fraud.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: iStock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001113428"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/imani-moise" itemprop="url" rel="author">Imani Moise</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/credit-card-payment-app-fraud-security-3188221b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Buyers have more ways to pay for things than ever before: <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="company-name">Apple</a> Pay, Venmo, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/credit-card-cost-fees-legislation-8782d2e9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">credit cards</a> and dozens of other options. What you choose might matter as much as the purchase itself.</p><p> Each of the different payment methods provides various conveniences, perks and protections from fraud. Credit cards have long been the default option of choice. But <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">higher interest rates</a> have now raised the cost of carrying a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/credit-card-car-debt-payments-behind-decc1a22?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">credit-card balance</a> .</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/teens-venmo-uber-amazon-accounts-5043f9d2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Money-transfer apps such as Venmo</a> and Zelle processed nearly $900 billion last year, and the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau expects that number to reach $1.6 trillion by 2027.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> These apps and services provide easy instant payments, usually for free. The downside is that these options offer fewer protections from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/jpmorgan-other-banks-in-talks-to-reimburse-scammed-zelle-customers-11669608886?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">scams and unfulfilled orders</a> .</p><p> “The US consumer is very driven by convenience. They may not be directly driven by security,” said James Anderson, managing director at Paze, a bank-owned digital wallet.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dont-forget-to-block-your-ex-on-your-payment-apps-207358bc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Payment apps</a> are among the fastest-growing sources of fraud reports and losses, according to Federal Trade Commission data. Overall fraud losses have increased more than fivefold to $1.2 trillion since 2019. Losses tied to payment apps jumped from $5 million to $47 million over the same period, according to the FTC data.</p><p> As new payment options gain acceptance, consumers should try to educate themselves how to use these methods safely, said Seth Ruden, director of global advisory at BioCatch, a fraud-detection software company.</p><p> “The channel itself is not the villain. The bad actors are the scammers, the social engineers and exploit artists,” he said.</p><p> Here&#39;s how to weigh the security, convenience and benefits of each payment option:</p><h3> Credit and debit cards</h3><p> When you swipe or tap your card or authorize a card transaction online, the merchant&#39;s bank communicates with your bank through a card network such as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MA" class="company-name">Mastercard</a> or <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/V" class="company-name">Visa</a> to ask permission to withdraw a certain amount.然后，您的银行根据您的可用资金或信用以及交易欺诈的可能性决定是否批准交易。 If approved, your bank puts a hold on the funds until they are sent to the merchant&#39;s account, usually within a business day.</p><p> Credit cards can be the most rewarding way to pay online. Card issuers use the revenue from transaction fees <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-pandemic-didnt-end-card-rewards-it-made-them-stronger-20fd03c9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to fund perks</a> for customers such as cash-back deals, travel points, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-lounge-battle-royale-coming-soon-to-your-airport-b09cf303?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">access to airport lounges</a> and fraud protection.</p><p> A credit card can be expensive if you don&#39;t pay your balance in full, and higher interest rates have now raised the cost of carrying a credit-card balance. Paying off a $1,000 balance in 12 months at the current average annual percentage rate of 22.16% means $103 in interest, compared with $77 roughly a year ago when the average was 16.65%, according to estimates from the Federal Reserve.</p><p> Debit cards don&#39;t offer the same rewards as credit cards since their issuers make less money from each transaction. They do come with similar fraud and payment protections as credit cards. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="468" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831153?width=700&amp;height=468" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Apps such as Zelle move money more quickly than card payments because the payment is authorized once the sender hits submit.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Tiffany Hagler-Geard/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Federal regulations require issuers to reimburse customers for unauthorized transactions of more than $50 and allow customers to dispute charges within 30 days. Many credit cards also provide purchase protection, meaning you can ask for reimbursements directly from your issuer if something you buy is lost, damaged or inconsistent with what was advertised.</p><p> Few people make the most of their credit-card benefits, payments experts said. After finding most people don&#39;t bother to read the fine print when they sign up for a new card, Mastercard is now notifying customers of benefits in real-time.</p><p> “If I have to read a big booklet or call a number to understand what my benefits are, I&#39;m not doing it,” said Chiro Aikat, executive vice president of US market development at Mastercard.</p><h3> Digital wallets</h3><p> Digital wallets such as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PYPL" class="company-name">PayPal</a> or Apple Pay are among the safest and easiest ways to pay online. Checking out with a wallet is typically faster than paying with a credit card directly since one doesn&#39;t have to re-enter billing information and shipping address.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Which payment method do you favor, and why?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> All of the protections and benefits associated with the underlying card are still in effect for wallet transactions, so it is best to connect these wallets to a credit card directly to maximize your protection, said Corie Wagner, an analyst at Security.org, a safety-product review site.</p><p> If a digital wallet gives you the option to link a bank account directly, you should read the policy agreement to make sure you understand what is protected. For example, PayPal offers an extra level of purchase protection, but Apple Pay and Google Pay don&#39;t.</p><p> Wallets also offer additional layers of security through encryption and biometric verification and many don&#39;t share sensitive financial data such as your 16-card number with individual merchants. “Use as many authentication factors as possible” such as Face ID or personal identification numbers, Wagner said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=F5C2DBC2-7CEB-4D03-BA48-E58580F05D20&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fcredit-card-payment-app-fraud-security-3188221b&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Tap-to-pay is growing in the US, thanks in part to its security and ease of use. But it&#39;s more complicated than it looks. WSJ takes you inside one of Square&#39;s card readers to break down the tech that powers contactless payments. Photo illustration: Xingpei Shen<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><h3>Peer-to-peer payment apps</h3><p> Apps such as Venmo, Cash App and Zelle were designed to help people send money to friends and family, but they are now used in more settings.它们比银行卡支付更快地转移资金，因为无需等待银行批准交易，而是在发送者点击“提交”后即可授权付款。 It is almost impossible to get money back once it has been sent.</p><p> These payment methods aren&#39;t regulated as heavily as cards, so users might still be on the hook for unauthorized payments if a swindler gets control of their accounts.</p><p> “Use it to pay people you know, and trust,” said Meghan Fintland, a Zelle spokeswoman. “They&#39;re not meant to have the credit-card security.”</p><h3> Bank transfers</h3><p> Businesses are increasingly offering ways to pay with your bank account directly since Automated Clearing House, or ACH, transfers are much cheaper to process than cards. This option should only be considered in exchange for a discount, payments executives said.</p><p> Consumers should be selective in sharing their bank information with merchants since wire transfers don&#39;t have the same protection guarantees as cards.</p><p> If a business requests a direct bank transfer instead of a card payment, choosing a slower option over the newer instant methods such as Zelle might be best. ACH transfers typically take a few days to settle, giving you a few more days to try to stop the transaction before the money leaves your account.</p><p> “The slower it is, the greater likelihood is that you&#39;ll be able to get recourse,” Ruden, at BioCatch, said.</p><p> Write to Imani Moise at <a href="mailto:imani.moise@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">imani.moise@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/credit-card-payment-app-fraud-security-3188221b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/credit-card-payment-app-fraud-security-3188221b<author><![CDATA[Imani Moise]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>Credit Types/Services</category><category> Credit Cards</category><category> Banking/Credit</category><category>金融服务</category><category>Financial Technology</category><category> Mobile Payment Systems</category><category> Electronic Payment Systems</category><category>技术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Fraud</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>fraud</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>credit types</category><category>服务</category><category>信用卡</category><category>banking</category><category>信用</category><category>financial services</category><category>金融科技</category><category>mobile payment systems</category><category> electronic payment systems</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘First to the Front’ Review: A Leading Lady of Journalism]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> One editor tagged her the &#39;bayonet border correspondent&#39; since she was usually among the first to arrive at a combat zone. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590126000121988496"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830547?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Dickey Chapelle photographs Marines in 1955.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Wisconsin Historical Society </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590126000121988496"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Charlotte Gray</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 7, 2023 5:58 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/first-to-the-front-review-a-leading-lady-of-journalism-abe61786"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> The life of Dickey Chapelle reads like a Hollywood movie. A pearl-earringed photojournalist and war correspondent confounds all stereotypes, breaking stories and outdoing the US Marines in bravery; she is honored by freedom fighters, consulted by Pentagon brass and rewarded with the Presidential Medal of Freedom before retiring to an emeritus professorship.</p><p> This all happened to the real Dickey Chapelle—born Georgette Meyer in Milwaukee in 1918—except for the Medal of Freedom and the professorship. Instead, Chapelle was killed in 1965 while on a patrol with a Marine platoon in Vietnam and was soon forgotten. Many of her reports and dispatches never made it to press, either because she couldn&#39;t find a news outlet for them or because censorship stifled them. She was patriotic, principled and tough to the point of recklessness. As Lorissa Rinehart describes in “First to the Front,” Chapelle insisted on seeing every story with her own eyes, describing events from the point of view of the grunts rather than the generals. “By every right,” Ms. Rinehart writes, “Dickey Chapelle should be a household name.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/9ff4b76d-bdcb-46cd-935f-e30ea391114c.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Obsessed since childhood by the thrill of flight, Chapelle was one of three women accepted into MIT&#39;s aeronautical-engineering class in 1934. She was bright, but more than that, she was intrepid. After flunking out of school (she preferred watching planes to designing them), she worked at a local air circus so she could take flying lessons. She soon realized that there was a market for articles about air shows, and after the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NYT" class="company-name">New York Times</a> ran one of her stories, the publicity chief of Howard Hughes&#39;s Transcontinental &amp; Western Air (later TWA) offered her a job as his assistant.</p><p> When war broke out in Europe in 1939, she “saw the world teetering on the precipice of a historical moment,” Ms. Rinehart tells us, “and knew she had to be a part of it.” Her ambition was to be a photojournalist, so she signed up for classes with TWA&#39;s publicity photographer. Anthony Chapelle was twice her age, charismatic, gregarious and a good teacher, and Dickey fell in love with him. The two married in 1940.</p><p> Dickey Chapelle&#39;s first chance to report on military maneuvers came in 1942, when Look magazine sent her to photograph the 14th Infantry Regiment training in the Panamanian jungle. She proved herself to be as tenacious and courageous as the trainees, shouldering her own heavy camera equipment through the stifling humidity and clouds of mosquitoes. But military censors back home blocked her photos from appearing in print, on the grounds that the images posed a threat to national security.</p><p> Her next chance at the front came in 1945, when she received a commission and official accreditation to travel to the Pacific theater. Up until then, no female photographer had been given access to combat zones; she began by attaching herself to the Navy&#39;s nursing corps, responsible for evacuating casualties to US hospitals. She soon elbowed her way to Pearl Harbor, and then to Iwo Jima, where she covered the Marines in battle. As she photographed the wounded being loaded onto a hospital ship and trained her lens on the young men bleeding to death, she honed the skill and steely detachment she needed to weave their stories together into a gripping narrative.</p><p> By now, Chapelle was completely bitten by the war-reporting bug. Her coverage focused on the soldiers, sailors, nurses, airmen, guerrillas and refugees whose lives had been seared by war. Part of her mission, she told her military escorts, was to convey the importance of blood donations back home. This immediately endeared her to everyone, “from the shiniest brass button to the dirtiest grunt boot,” as Ms. Rinehart puts it. However, her success in capturing the action, despite orders to stay on the hospital ship, resulted in her press credentials being rescinded. Few of her pieces were published.</p><p> After the war, she persuaded the Quakers to send her on an extended trip to Eastern Europe to photograph families, and particularly children, traumatized by war and its outcomes—starvation, homelessness, sickness. Within years, prestigious publications such as National Geographic were using her photos and stories. In 1956, while covering the Hungarian Revolution, she was captured and jailed for six weeks, including five in solitary confinement. The experience left her psychologically wounded and turned her hostility toward totalitarian regimes into a fierce determination, Ms. Rinehart writes, “to beat back the tide of communism” and tell “the stories of others fighting for their freedom.”</p><p> Chapelle&#39;s mission would lead her to embed herself with the Algerian rebels in their fight against French rule, and with Fidel Castro&#39;s</p> guerrilla army in the Cuban Revolution. One editor tagged her the “bayonet border correspondent” since she was usually among the first at the front. By 1961, she was reporting on the American forces&#39; efforts to repel the Viet Cong. By the time of her death in 1965, she had grown exasperated by what she saw as the inability of US military leaders to understand guerilla warfare, and the CIA&#39;s complicity in the illegal expansion of the war. But military censorship prevented her from reporting about her outrage. “Perhaps Dickey should have known she was about to walk into one of the darkest periods of American history,” Ms. Rinehart writes. But she could not turn back, due to “her own naivete or fear or desire to believe that America could still be a beacon for freedom.”<p></p><p> “First to the Front” tells an extraordinary story with a great sense of drama and lots of gruesome details. It is hard to tell where many of those details came from because there are no footnotes. Instead, the author lists the primary sources for each chapter, almost all of which are Chapelle&#39;s own notes, letters, articles and her autobiography (originally titled “What&#39;s a Woman Doing Here?”). So the story is told almost exclusively from Chapelle&#39;s point of view, with (presumably) flourishes of color by the author but without comment from Chapelle&#39;s editors, peers or contacts—who no doubt admired her work but may have been irritated by her appetite for risk and her missionary zeal. To those who were the focus of her coverage, however, Dickey Chapelle was always a hero. At her Milwaukee funeral, the first for an American female journalist to be killed in combat, a Marine honor guard attended in full dress.</p><p> <em>Ms. Gray is the author of “Passionate Mothers, Powerful Sons: The Lives of Jennie Jerome Churchill and Sara Delano Roosevelt,” which will be published in September.</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 21:58:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/first-to-the-front-review-a-leading-lady-of-journalism-abe61786</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/first-to-the-front-review-a-leading-lady-of-journalism-abe61786<category>艺术</category><category>Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>Photography</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category>艺术</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>艺术</category><category>entertainment</category><category>摄影</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Chrome Dreams’ by Neil Young Review: From Bootleg to Banner Release]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The musician&#39;s new album, a collection recorded for release in the &#39;70s but then abandoned, cements his place among that decade&#39;s best singer-songwriters. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12165777042486313942804590136211558677190"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830590?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Neil Young</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Danny Clinch </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12165777042486313942804590136211558677190"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Mark Richardson</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 7, 2023 5:50 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chrome-dreams-by-neil-young-review-from-bootleg-to-banner-release-47e258ce"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Music obsessives of a certain stripe—the type of people who make endless Top 5 lists and recognize themselves in the characters from the 2000 film “High Fidelity,” say—like to argue about the best band or act of a given decade. The Beatles in the &#39;60s is a common choice, as is Prince in the &#39;80s. Competition is especially fierce in the &#39;70s, the height of the LP era, when music sat at the center of the pop-culture conversation. Stevie Wonder ? Excellent choice, probably the most logical. David Bowie ? Also reasonable, especially considering how his stature has grown in the past 15 years. Or Led Zeppelin, a band that changed the sound of hard rock? Or maybe even soul singer Al Green, a master of consistency whose first seven albums of the decade hardly had a weak song? But we also have to consider Neil Young. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830580?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div><p> During that decade, the Canadian singer-songwriter released eight studio albums and another studio LP with Stephen Stills ; he recorded with Crosby, Stills &amp; Nash; he issued a live album, “Time Fades Away” (1973), filled with all-new songs, many of which are brilliant, and another, “Live Rust” (1979), that&#39;s considered among the best in-concert rock albums ever made. Based purely on what came out at the time, it&#39;s a hugely impressive decade of work, more than enough to put Mr. Young in the running for the most important artist of the &#39;70s. But those official releases aren&#39;t the entire story.</p><p> Mr. Young recorded constantly in the &#39;70s and made decisions based on instinct, scrapping projects at the last minute for reasons known only to him. Several LPs from the period were readied for release and then abandoned, and for hardcore fans, these obscurities have become the stuff of legend. In the past few years, as part of his Neil Young Archives project, Mr. Young has issued several of these “lost albums.” The latest of these, “Chrome Dreams” (Reprise), out Friday, was originally considered for release in 1977, and was later bootlegged. It&#39;s a fantastic collection of songs that, had it been issued in this form, would have been considered in the upper tier of Mr. Young&#39;s catalog.</p><p> All the songs on “Chrome Dreams” eventually came out in one form or another over the years. Some were re-recorded or overdubbed for later issue, while others appear here in the same form as on later releases. The earliest part of the record has the most familiar titles, but the sequencing of “Chrome Dreams” makes them sound new. The set opens with “Pocahontas,” a song that would later become a highlight on “Rust Never Sleeps” and ranks with the most beautiful of Mr. Young&#39;s career. On “Rust,” the song is bathed in reverb with a halo of backing vocals and sound effects. It&#39;s the same recording of Mr. Young&#39;s voice and guitar as is found here, but with additional production. On the raw recording from “Chrome Dreams,” the starkness of this take lends the song an additional sense of loneliness and melancholy.</p><p> The hushed “Will to Love” is next, and it barely rises above a whisper; then the downcast “Star of Bethlehem,” which recalls the countrified lope of Mr. Young&#39;s early-&#39;70s material, rounds out the exceptionally mellow opening triptych. This reverie is interrupted by the eight-minute “Like a Hurricane,” a midtempo rocker built as a showcase for Mr. Young&#39;s noisy and knotty electric guitar leads. These three songs, in a different order, opened the second side of Mr. Young&#39;s “American Stars &#39;n Bars,” the album he released instead of “Chrome Dreams,” but hearing them after the opening “Pocahontas” elevates the material, driving home just how strong Mr. Young&#39;s songwriting was during this era.</p><p> The second half of the record ranges from “Captain Kennedy,” which has the flavor of an ancient folk tune and was later included on “Hawks &amp; Doves” (1980); to the gorgeous piano ballad “Stringman,” which was unreleased until 1993, when Mr. Young issued the recording of his “MTV Unplugged” performance; to a slower, bluesier version of “Sedan Delivery,” which appeared in a different recording on “Rust Never Sleeps.” The take of this last track, which hasn&#39;t been released before, is heavier, with a primordial guitar riff that recalls Link Wray&#39;s “Rumble.” “Powderfinger,” another song that appeared on “Rust” in a full-band arrangement, is a Young solo here. While it has none of the other version&#39;s swagger, it puts Mr. Young&#39;s lovely melody in the foreground to poignant effect.</p><p> Though Mr. Young is one of the sharpest songwriters in rock history, he&#39;s also something of a collage artist, someone who makes brilliant albums by assembling pieces in a particular juxtaposition. “No one ever mentioned that we were doin&#39; an album ever,” said guitarist Frank Sampedro of Mr. Young&#39;s backing band Crazy Horse about this period. “We just played and recorded.” Would it have made a difference in Mr. Young&#39;s career if he had released these songs in this order in 1977? It&#39;s impossible to say, but the fact that a record this strong was shelved and then stripped for parts says a lot about how many ideas Mr. Young had in those heady days.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Richardson is the Journal&#39;s rock and pop music critic. Follow him on Twitter @MarkRichardson.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 21:50:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chrome-dreams-by-neil-young-review-from-bootleg-to-banner-release-47e258ce</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chrome-dreams-by-neil-young-review-from-bootleg-to-banner-release-47e258ce<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Concerts</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>concerts</category><category>艺术</category><category>entertainment</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Real-Estate Haven Turns Perilous With $1 Trillion Coming Due]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>公寓楼的价值多年来一直上涨，但飙升的利率现在笼罩着该行业的业主<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830485/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="随着租金稳步上涨，投资者抬高了多户住宅的价格。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>随着租金稳步上涨，投资者抬高了多户住宅的价格。理查德·B·莱文/祖玛出版社<span>理查德·B·莱文/祖玛出版社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001112088"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001112088"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/konrad-putzier" itemprop="url" rel="author">康拉德·普齐尔</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/will-parker" itemprop="url" rel="author">威尔·帕克</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 7 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>长期以来被认为是房地产天堂的公寓楼正在成为陷入困境的商业地产领域的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/houston-apartment-owner-loses-3-200-units-to-foreclosure-as-multifamily-feels-the-heat-fb3d0e75?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">下一个主要麻烦点</a>。</p><p>多年来，受租金稳步上涨和巨额回报前景的吸引，投资者不断抬高多户住宅的价格。许多人承担了过多的债务，期望能够以足够快的速度提高租金来偿还债务。</p><p>与受到远程工作和电子商务严重打击的写字楼和商场不同，出租公寓的空置率较低。公寓行业的主要问题不是缺乏需求——自 2020 年以来租金飙升——而是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/investors-bet-that-high-rates-will-linger-61cdaeb7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">利率</a>。</p><p>去年债务成本的突然飙升现在有可能使全国许多多户家庭业主破产。数据公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CSGP" class="">CoStar</a>的数据显示，继去年上涨 25% 后，截至 6 月份的一年中，公寓楼价值下降了 14% <span class="company-name-type">。</span>这一下降幅度与写字楼价值的下降幅度大致相同。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830530?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">许多公寓楼投资者承担了过多的债务，期望他们能够足够快地提高租金来偿还债务。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：大卫·保罗·莫里斯/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>多户住宅类别的抵押贷款拖欠率较低，但仍在增加。借贷成本翻了一番，租金增长放缓，建筑费用上升。数据提供商特雷普今年早些时候发现，在面临违约风险的商业抵押贷款中，一类出租公寓债务占很大比例。</p><p> Apartment landlords face a “hydrogen-bomb scenario,” said Peter Sotoloff, a veteran real-estate finance executive, a former founding member of Blackstone&#39;s property debt business and former managing partner at Mack Real Estate Credit Strategies.<br><br>根据抵押贷款银行家协会的数据，未偿还的多户抵押贷款在过去十年中增加了一倍多，达到约 2 万亿美元。特雷普表示，这几乎是办公室债务的两倍。该数据提供商补充说，9807 亿美元的多户家庭债务预计将在 2023 年至 2027 年间到期。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830785?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “每个人都专注于办公室，”索托洛夫说。他补充说，公寓违约的风险“是一个非常大的问题，但没有得到应有的关注。”</p><p>洛杉矶、休斯顿和旧金山的多户住宅业主拖欠了数千套公寓的贷款。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BX" class="">Blackstone</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> the world&#39;s largest alternative-asset manager, is in special servicing on mortgages related to 11 Manhattan apartment buildings, according to a person familiar with the matter. Blackstone 的一位发言人表示，这些建筑存在独特的问题，“不能代表我们在更广泛的租赁住房组合中看到的实力。”</p><p>公寓楼被誉为风险较低的商业房地产投资。即使在经济衰退时期，包括2008-2009年金融危机期间房地产市场崩溃时，它们的表现也相对较好。人们总是需要一个地方居住，在危机时期，前房主会涌入租赁市场。</p><p>通货膨胀还使房东能够比平时提高租金，从而推高了其建筑物的价值。根据租赁网站 Apartment List 的数据，2021 年至 2022 年 18 个月内，租金要价上涨了 25%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=88CDF171-D046-4FD4-A4BB-72130DCCB4C6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fa-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">由于住房供应短缺，开发商正在将更多空置办公室改造成公寓。但并非所有建筑物都适合重复利用，尽管美国各地有超过 10 亿平方英尺的办公空间闲置 图片插图：Amber Bragdon<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>对于许多投资者来说，这些因素<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rising-interest-rates-concern-apartment-building-owners-renters-11653393600?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">证明支付高价是合理的</a>。公寓楼业主通常从债券市场借入超过 80% 的建筑价值。大多数公寓贷款都是固定利率的长期抵押贷款。然而，在疫情期间，投资者获得了更多<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bonds-backed-by-apartments-are-under-stress-as-housing-market-cools-9717d617?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">短期浮动利率贷款</a>。</p><p>许多投资者大幅提高租金，押注一旦他们的建筑物产生更高的租金收入，他们就可以以更高的估值出售建筑物或为债务再融资。</p><p>但很少有人预料到利率会上升得如此之快，从而压低建筑价值并迫使房东以更高的利率进行再融资。作为重要资金来源的地区性银行如今的放贷量大幅减少，导致抵押贷款再融资变得更加困难。美国许多城市<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/renters-are-about-to-get-the-upper-hand-f6387df4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的租金增长大幅放缓</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/renters-are-about-to-get-the-upper-hand-f6387df4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，</a>而通货膨胀和保险费上涨则提高了建筑物的运营成本。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830093?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>主要由浮动利率债务和小投资者现金资助的一批新的私人房地产公司已成为多户住宅市场上更大的竞争对手。一些人基于对未来几年租金大幅上涨的乐观预期而支付了更高的价格。现在，他们在使数字发挥作用方面遇到了困难。</p><p>总部位于洛杉矶的 Tides Equities 自 2016 年以来已收购了价值超过 65 亿美元的租赁房产，其中大部分是西南部城市的中低收入公寓楼。评级机构报告显示，2021 年，该公司预计达拉斯郊区的一处房产的租金将在三年内上涨 44%。<br><br> 6 月，Tides 告诉投资者，该战略并未按计划进行。该公司在一封信中表示，租户“现金变得过于紧张”。信中称，一些房产不再赚取足够的钱来偿还债务，投资者可能需要投入更多资金来挽救建筑物免于违约。</p><p> Tides 联合创始人 Sean Kia 和 Ryan Andrade 在接受采访时表示，他们正在与贷方合作，寻找避免面临困难的房产违约的方法。</p><p>总部位于休斯敦的 Nitya Capital 拥有价值约 30 亿美元的多户住宅，该公司在 3 月份通知投资者，由于利率上升，该公司将大幅削减利润预期。</p><p> Nitya 首席执行官 Swapnil Agarwal 在一封投资者信中写道：“我们实际上是在支付更高的抵押贷款成本，而不是进行现金分配。”</p><p>公寓业主仍有理由保持乐观。即使银行撤退，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/FNMA" class="company-name">房利美</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/FMCC" class="company-name">房地美</a>仍能提供政府支持的可靠贷款来源。大多数分析师预计住房短缺和高租金将持续存在。如果利率下降，房地产价格可能会迅速反弹。拥有固定利率抵押贷款的多户家庭业主更有能力度过任何近期的动荡。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您对商业地产的前景有何看法？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>尽管如此，其他威胁仍在加剧。今年和明年开业的新公寓楼数量异常多，特别是在高端租赁市场，引起了供应方面的担忧。</p><p> CoStar资本市场分析全国总监查德·利特尔(Chad Littell)表示，此外，公寓楼价值比商业楼宇价值更容易受到利率上涨的影响，因为它们与10年期国债价格密切相关，而随着利率上升，十年期国债价格暴跌。</p><p>即使是一些经历过风暴的资深房地产投资者也显得很脆弱。旧金山最大的房东之一<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NZ/XNZE/GSH" class="">Veritas Investments</a><span class="company-name-type">及其</span>合作伙伴在过去一年中拖欠了 95 栋出租建筑的债务。结果，该公司将损失超过三分之一的旧金山投资组合。</p><p>该公司今年早些时候表示，“多户型房地产行业正面临着许多与其他资产类别（包括办公楼、零售业和酒店业）相同的财务挑战。”</p><p>写信给 Konrad Putzier <a href="mailto:konrad.putzier@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（konrad.putzier@wsj.com）</a>和 Will Parker（ <a href="mailto:will.parker@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">will.parker@wsj.com</a> ）</p><p id="correction" class="correction"><strong>更正和放大</strong><br>Blackstone&#39;s portfolio of 11 Manhattan apartment buildings is in special servicing. A previous version of this story incorrectly said they are in default. (Corrected on Aug. 7)</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528<author><![CDATA[Konrad PutzierWill Parker]]></author><category>住房</category><category>商业地产</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>住房</category><category>商业房地产</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>黑色的石头</category><category>巴克斯</category><category>房利美</category><category>国家气象局</category><category>房地美</category><category>FMCC</category><category>科星集团</category><category>CSGP</category><category>良好的精神好客</category><category>谷胱甘肽新西兰</category><category>新西兰：还原型谷胱甘肽</category><category>彼得·索托洛夫</category><category>肖恩·基亚</category><category>瑞安·安德拉德</category><category>斯瓦普尼尔·阿加瓦尔</category><category>查德·利特尔</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Anansi’s Gold’ Review: Treasure Map to Nowhere]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>他知道如何找到加纳领导人向国外汇出的数十亿美元，但首先他需要投资者来让他（奢侈地）维持生计。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590122110697799470"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830546?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">约翰·布莱-米扎。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Yepoka Yeebo </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590122110697799470"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">弗兰克·<span class="author" itemprop="name">甘农</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 6 日下午 4:58 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/anansis-gold-review-treasure-map-to-nowhere-a3990d04"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> 20 世纪 70 年代中期，一位名叫约翰·布莱-米扎 (John Blay-Miezah) 的富有魅力的加纳年轻人在伦敦、纽约和费城闲逛。这位彬彬有礼的宾夕法尼亚大学毕业生，现年 30 岁出头，有一个惊人的故事要讲，也有一笔非凡的交易。</p><p>他向所有愿意倾听的人讲述了 1972 年 4 月，他在布加勒斯特陪伴加纳首任总统夸梅·恩克鲁玛临终的情景。在生命的最后时刻，这位流亡领袖向他的部落兄弟和门生吐露了这个传闻已久的故事是真的：在 1966 年被政变推翻之前，他成功盗取了数十亿美元的钻石、现金，尤其是 30,000 美元。从加纳到瑞士银行的金条。这笔钱专门用于他深爱的国家的改善项目，并将留在国外，直到某个更稳定的时刻可以安全地遣返。只有布莱-米扎知道账号、密码以及访问宝藏所需的程序。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><p><strong>阿纳西的黄金</strong></p><p><em>作者：叶波卡·伊博</em></p><p><em>（布卢姆斯伯里，378 页，29.99 美元）</em> </p></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/e84b6b53-c858-469a-9713-9d8c94f25e4e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>布莱-米扎告诉听众，他现在已准备好执行恩克鲁玛的指示，并且他相信只需要几周甚至最多几个月就能拿到这笔钱。与此同时，他正在寻找人来支付他的开支。他并不指望美德本身会得到回报，因为除了帮助一个陷入困境的非洲国家的满足感之外，投资者还可以保证获得惊人的回报：每投资一美元，回报率为 10 比 1、20 比 1，甚至 100 比 1。支持者和投资者并不难找到——从贫穷的寡妇到前美国司法部长约翰·米切尔（1979 年出狱后的他）。钱就涌进来了。</p><p>但布莱-米扎的故事存在问题。首先，他最接近在宾夕法尼亚大学学习的经历是在费城联合联盟俱乐部当服务员。他没有在罗马尼亚恩克鲁玛的临终病床上，而是在费城郊外一个小时的格拉特福德州立惩教所因欺诈罪而服刑。</p><p>首次入读英国裔加纳作家耶波卡·伊博 (Yepoka Yeebo) 在《安纳西的黄金：掠夺西方、智胜华盛顿、欺骗世界的人》一书中，以辛辣的沉着讲述了布莱-米扎的夸张生活和任性的职业生涯。伊博女士认出布莱-米扎就是神秘的加纳骗子阿南西。就像中国的孙悟空一样，阿南西用他的诡计来欺骗和欺骗更大、更强的人。虽然《阿纳西的黄金》反映了大量令人畏惧的研究，但它读起来就像一本流浪汉小说。</p><p>据 Yeebo 女士记载，近二十年来，Blay-Miezah 一直通过揭露阻碍他获得资金的令人讨厌的新技术来拉拢投资者。很快，一种模式就出现了。经过无休止的拖延后，投资者将被召集到加纳（或瑞士或开曼群岛），期待已久的付款终于在那里发生。几天后，布莱-米扎就会消失。最终他会在其他地方重新出现，循环又会开始。</p><p>伊博女士指出，美国驻加纳大使秀兰·邓波儿·布莱克（Shirley Temple Black）看穿了布莱-米扎并试图警告其他人。在 1975 年给国务卿亨利·基辛格的一封电报中，她解释了这个问题：“那些认为布莱-米扎是骗子的人担心他可能只是有钱，然后他们就会显得极其愚蠢。”</p><p>布莱-米扎是个大人物，生活也很大。他的定制西装、镶满珠宝的手指、时尚的豪华轿车、私人厨师和顶层套房增加了他的神秘感，而不是削弱了他的可信度。他对投资者（以及他的妻子，她因追踪他的调情的巧妙方法而被昵称为“科伦坡”）不忠诚，但他始终忠于自己内心的骗子。适时地制造健康恐慌是他的惯用伎俩。伊博女士描述了他在一家医院里的情况，监视器发出蜂鸣声，脸上戴着氧气面罩：“布莱-米扎睁开眼睛迎接来访者。一位投资者向他提供了一叠现金。他一动不动，除了右手慢慢地从床单下面伸出来，抓住现金，然后又消失在床单下面。”</p><p> 1979 年，布莱-米扎找到了一种逃避起诉并获得大量资源的方法：他将成为加纳总统。他不受事实束缚，不受现实约束，以反腐败候选人的身份参选。当他看起来确实有机会获胜时，政府以贿赂、伪证和伪造罪名起诉他。为了确定起见，他的名字已从选票中删除。</p><p>对于一个较轻的骗子来说，有罪判决和九年监禁将是终结。但前方仍然有许多擦伤和逃跑。最终，是埃德·布拉德利和《60 分钟》击败了布莱-米扎。该片段于 1989 年 1 月播出，标题为“终极骗子”。布莱-米扎本人可能是迷人且令人信服的。在电视上，他被认为是虚伪且荒谬的。三年后，他因心脏病发作而死——或者正如伊博女士所说，他可能没有死。不管怎样，葬礼还是举行了，1993 年，一个长得很像他的人被埋葬在阿克拉。</p><p>虽然伊博女士的叙述引人入胜，但她的一些后殖民分析却值得商榷。她忽略了过高利润的明显动机，写道布莱-米扎的黑人投资者希望“修复殖民主义的创伤”，而他的白人投资者则看到了“掠夺非洲国家祖传财富”的机会。</p><p>反常的是，布莱-米扎骗局的力量和恩克鲁玛黄金的诱惑依然存在。 2009 年，加纳政府的一个官方委员会没有发现任何证据表明黄金曾经存在过。但贪婪是永恒的，伊博女士指出，“现在，在世界的某个地方，有人正在撒布莱-米扎关于恩克鲁玛黄金的谎言，有人正在投资它。”</p><p><em>甘农先生是尼克松白宫的总统特别助理。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 20:58:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/anansis-gold-review-treasure-map-to-nowhere-a3990d04</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/anansis-gold-review-treasure-map-to-nowhere-a3990d04<category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>entertainment</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Bark Out Thunder Roar Out Lightning’ and ‘Lowcountry’ Reviews: Southern Stories Renewed Through Jazz]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Trumpeter Chief Adjuah, formerly known as Christian Scott, sets aside his usual instrument and embraces his Black Indian heritage on a new album; Lowcountry&#39;s self-titled record combines modern jazz with the musical traditions of Gullah culture. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590116052446285656"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="1290" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829927?width=860&amp;height=1290" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Chief Xian aTunde Adjuah</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ropeadope Records </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590116052446285656"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Larry Blumenfeld</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 5, 2023 7:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bark-out-thunder-roar-out-lightning-and-lowcountry-reviews-southern-stories-renewed-through-jazz-883d20d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> In the American South, music recovers histories, especially of African-American traditions, and sometimes reinvents them. Two new releases (both on Ropeadope)— <strong>“Bark Out Thunder Roar Out Lightning,”</strong> from Chief Adjuah (formerly Christian Scott ); and <strong>“Lowcountry,”</strong> by a collective with that name—reflect this truth with force and beauty.</p><p> Christian Scott grew up in the Upper Ninth Ward of New Orleans. His grandfather, Donald Harrison Sr. , was a Big Chief of Black Indian culture, in which ancestral history, personal independence and community cohesion are expressed through chants and declarations, along with hand-drummed rhythms and elaborate feathered-and-beaded suits. His uncle, Donald Harrison Jr. , best known as an alto saxophonist and a standard-bearer of modern jazz, is also a Big Chief.</p><p> Before Mr. Adjuah picked up the trumpet with which, as Christian Scott, he has earned widespread acclaim, he was immersed in this familial tradition. (He became a chief himself in 2017.) On his new release, as Chief Adjuah (drawn from his full adopted legal name, Xian aTunde Adjuah ), he plays no trumpet at all. On “Blood Calls Blood,” he opens the album strumming “Chief Adjuah&#39;s Bow,” a 20-string electric instrument that blends elements of two West African instruments, the <em>n&#39;goni</em> and <em>kora</em> , with those of a European harp. Ninety seconds in, he sings, for the first time on record: “Listen in the wind have you learned to hear / The voices callin&#39; to you from yesteryear.”</p><p> Mr. Adjuah mines a tradition built on rhythms and vocals. Here, eight drummers and percussionists—whose instruments include a standard trap set, a “pan-African kit” and more than a dozen kinds of hand drums—represent various connected musical cultures: Joe Dyson Jr. , a New Orleans native, is a rising jazz star; Weedie Braimah, born in Ghana, is a master of the West African <em>djembe</em> . Mr. Adjuah sings on all but one track.</p><p> Honoring one&#39;s lineage is also a central aspect of this culture. “Shallow Water,” an anthem of Black Indian culture, was popularized by Mr. Adjuah&#39;s grandfather; his own lyrics to “Ashé Chief Donald” celebrate his uncle&#39;s achievements. His version of the oft-recorded R&amp;B song “ Iko Iko ” (here, titled “Xodokan Iko— Hu Na Ney ”) hews close to how it is sung in street processions, rich with overlapping calls-and-responses and organic shifts of meter.</p><p> Mr. Adjuah&#39;s original compositions are hypnotic—dreamy on “End Simulation,” and with an air of menace on “Trouble That Mornin&#39;.” The 15-minute-plus title track forms the album&#39;s emotional core. Here, his custom-made bow sounds as percussive as Mr. Braimah&#39;s drums, his singing proud yet pained, and his lyrics pointed: “I think you can&#39;t outrun those fires born of the violence.”</p><p> Black Indian tradition has had notable crossover moments: In the 1970s, albums by Bo Dollis&#39;s Wild Magnolias and the Wild Tchoupitoulas made it visionary funk; Donald Harrison Jr.&#39;s 1992 release, “Indian Blues,” distilled it into jazz. Mr. Adjuah broadens this reach, and makes a mesmerizing personal statement about entwined histories of African empires, Native American nations, New Orleans forebears, and his own life and times.</p><h4> *** </h4><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829973?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Members of the Gullah-influenced jazz ensemble Lowcountry</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ropeadope Records</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Trumpeter Matt White, who is chair of jazz studies at the University of South Carolina, knew little about Gullah culture when, a decade ago, he made field recordings of elders on St. Helena Island. Entranced by the traditional songs of the Gullah people—descendants of enslaved West Africans in the Lowcountry regions and Sea Islands of the Deep South. He kept returning.</p><p> Gullah songs have long influenced American music—from George Gershwin&#39;s opera “Porgy and Bess” to the Grammy-winning band Ranky Tanky. Mr. White aims both to preserve Gullah songs and to reimagine them. The Lowcountry collective he assembled is anchored by Quentin Baxter,</p> Ranky Tanky&#39;s drummer, who deftly blends the Gullah beats of his upbringing in Charleston, SC, with modern-jazz mastery.<p></p><p> These tracks are set in motion by Gracie Gadsen and Joseph and Rosa Murray, who are husband and wife. They are all “song leaders” in Gullah tradition, who “line and raise” melodies learned from elders, mostly at Praise House services. Mr. White recorded them narrating cultural histories and singing Gullah songs in their homes. He then crafted arrangements, for which he gathered jazz musicians and, on six tracks, the Charleston Symphony String Quartet, in a recording studio. He wove these elements together, often to seamless effect. On four tracks, the celebrated tenor saxophonist Chris Potter, who grew up in Columbia, SC, becomes another sort of song leader, his improvisations forming the calls for other musicians&#39; responses.</p><p> On “ Aye Neva, ” an old “shouting song,” Mr. Murray sings the Gullah phrase “day come clean” (signaling the start of the day), repeating it like a chant. Mr. Potter turns the notes and cadence into a melodic cell. As embellished by the jazz ensemble and string players—13 musicians in all—the harmonies change hues, not unlike a sunrise. Soon, Mr. Baxter syncopates bass-drum kicks with beats of his tambourine, an instrument he first played as a boy in church.</p><p> Before any of this music, Gullah musician and cultural preservationist Ron Daise</p> recites an original poem, “Forgotten Moments”: “A history of a people has been hushed,” he says. “Progress and short-sightedness are silencing a heritage.” To end the album, “Come By Here,” the Gullah traditional best known as “Kumbaya,” becomes a ballad, highlighted by Mr. White&#39;s sweet-toned fluegelhorn set against pizzicato strings.<p></p><p> With reverence and unhushed abandon, Chief Adjuah and Lowcountry extend legacies that, however threatened or overlooked, are still very much alive.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Blumenfeld writes about jazz and Afro-Latin music for the Journal.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 05 Aug 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bark-out-thunder-roar-out-lightning-and-lowcountry-reviews-southern-stories-renewed-through-jazz-883d20d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bark-out-thunder-roar-out-lightning-and-lowcountry-reviews-southern-stories-renewed-through-jazz-883d20d<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>entertainment</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews</category></item></channel></rss>